## 2. Memory Leaks

Memory leaks are a common problem in C programs. A memory leak occurs when a program allocates memory but does not free it when it is done with it. This results in the program using more and more memory over time, eventually causing the program to run out of memory and crash.

To demonstrate a memory leak, we will create a program that allocates memory and then does not free it.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    // allocate a new integer
    int *p = (int *)malloc(sizeof(int));
    // set the value of the integer to 5
	*p = 5;
    // print the value of the integer
	printf("Value: %d\n", *p);
    // do not free the memory
	return 0;
}
```

Output:

```
Value: 5
```

As you can see, the program allocated memory for an integer and set its value to 5. However, it did not free the memory. This means that the program is using more and more memory over time, eventually causing the program to run out of memory and crash.

To fix this memory leak, we need to free the memory when we are done with it. We can do this by adding a call to free() after we are done with the memory.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    // allocate a new integer
    int *p = (int *)malloc(sizeof(int));
    // set the value of the integer to 5
	*p = 5;
    // print the value of the integer
	printf("Value: %d\n", *p);
    // free the memory
	free(p);
    return 0;
}
```

Output:

```
Value: 5
```

Now the program has freed the memory and the memory leak is fixed.

## 3. Memory Management in C

C provides several functions for allocating and freeing memory. The most common functions are:

- malloc() - allocates memory
- calloc() - allocates memory and sets all bytes to 0
- realloc() - changes the size of an allocated memory block
- free() - frees an allocated memory block

These functions are defined in the standard library header file stdlib.h.

