The heap is a region of memory that is used to dynamically allocate memory. The heap is typically used to store large amounts of data that are not known at compile time.

The heap is a first-in, first-out (FIFO) data structure. This means that the first item placed on the heap is the first item popped off the heap.

The heap is a limited resource. The heap size is typically limited to the amount of available memory, and the heap is typically used by all threads.

